 Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Yiddish <i>ber</i> ‘bear’, probably influenced by the early medieval European practice of giving animal names to people. It is often paired with   Dov   in order to provide a Hebrew name in certain rituals."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicolas Ier de Barbencon was born about 1140, his father, Isaac II de Barbancon, was 57 and his mother, Mahaut de Rumigny, was 37. He married Helvide de Saint-Aubert before 1170, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1195, in France, at the age of 56."},"et":{"about 1140–1195":"umbes 1140–1195","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1140–1195":"1140–1195","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1256":"1175–1256","1085–1135":"1085–1135","1105–1135":"1105–1135","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1256":"1256","1123":"1123","1145":"1145","before 1170":"enne 1170","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1140–1195":"noin 1140–1195","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1140–1195":"1140–1195","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1256":"1175–1256","1085–1135":"1085–1135","1105–1135":"1105–1135","about 1140":"noin 1140","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1256":"1256","1123":"1123","1145":"1145","before 1170":"ennen vuotta 1170","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1140–1195":"environ 1140–1195","1125–1195":"1125–1195","1140–1195":"1140–1195","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1256":"1175–1256","1085–1135":"1085–1135","1105–1135":"1105–1135","about 1140":"environ 1140","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","11